<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> On the one hand you claim these high level people are stealing your spawn.. on the other hand your basically pointing out that its your spawn because you were there for 8+ or whatever hours camping it. Hey thats your choice, I would rather be getting steady exp and ok loot somewhere else so I could level.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Wait a minute, did you read my rant? I got a ton of experience in Permafrost at that level, as well as regular drops of ringmail, bronze armor, various words, gems and assorted other loot. Great experience and great loot, if you can keep from dying. The greatest risks yield the greatest rewards, and the greatest fun, IMO. How is spending 8 hours doing this any different at all from spending eight hours camping treants? Or DE guards? Or dwarves? Or roaming SK mobs? The only difference is, hunting for exp and loot near these rare spawns in Perma also might yield a valuble piece of loot that my wife or I can use.<br>
<br>
You're absolutely right. I don't own the spawn, and I do have to share. But somebody zoning in, charging past me and killing a rare mob I was preparing to take down isn't sharing. Not in any polite sense, anyway. If they had walked up and sent me a tell along the lines of &quot;I would like to kill the scryer, may I?&quot; then thanks to PNP I'd be hard put to refuse. Admittedly I would probably look at the scryer and see if he was toting a staff before replying either &quot;Sure, go ahead.&quot; or &quot;Alright, you can have the next one.&quot; If I refused to share then the newcomer might be within his rights to go ahead and just kill it anyway, but it would still be rude, which was the point of my entire rant.<br>
<br>
Now I realize at this point your argument would be &quot;I don't own the spawn, I have no right to refuse or allow another player to attack the spawn.&quot; True, but the issue was not really spawn ownership, it was politeness. Everquest is a social game, and in order for everybody to have fun, people need to behave as they would in any real social gathering. Rudeness breeds unhappiness. The only time rudeness would be socially acceptable would be in a PvP or RP environment, neither of which do I participate in. Ironically, though, most PvP'ers and RP'ers I've met have been utterly polite and likeable people. They generally won't kill you outright when you would obviously suffer a near impossible CR, for instance.<br>
<br>
A real world analogy would be riding a bus. I don't own a bus seat, even if I sat there first. If you are bigger than me, you could easily displace me and take the seat away from me, and I could do nothing about it. That doesn't make it right for you to do so.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I happen to like playing a mage much more.. lots more fun.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Agreed.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> If your not in one of these guilds you don't go to the plains. This is the way it will always be because the Plains are a tough place that requires organization. Spawns are not shared there.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Not necessarily true. A single group of sufficient level and balance could easily go to Hate and hunt it like a regular zone. It happens all the time, especially on servers like my old one which had no mutually agreed upon calendar of events to decide who goes when. In fact, one time I was in Hate hunting regular mobs when another guild asked if they could come in and take down the Maestro and Inny. We said sure, go right ahead. We even shared some armor drops we didn't need with them, and vice versa. <br>
<br>
The reason plane raids tend to be single guild affairs is not so much an issue of organization or difficulty. It's because when you have 80+ people in a zone (ANY zone) players with less than broadband connections tend to get dropped or suffer lag so bad they can't play properly. If you're having lag problems in East Commons or even Karnor's you can always just leave. Not so in the planes, where many classes are incapable of zoning out without assistance or dying.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> They made the policy I did not.. and if they change it I will abide by it. Sure I wait my turn, when its worth it. If its not I leave and go somewhere else.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->So what's the issue here then? This is exactly what I do, and I think it's fair to expect others to do the same. The GMs probably would side with the guy stealing the scryer, because he was within his rights to do so according to the rules of the game. All I was asking for in my rant was a little common courtesy. Courtesy isn't required by the rules at all, which is why I posted a rant here instead of /petitioning.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I'm glad your not on the same server... one less self-centered person to deal with.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Agreed. <p><p><font face="Arial" COLOR="blue" size="2"><b>Nefarius Frobozz</b><br>Devout Agnostic Gnome Magician of the 31st Trial<i><br>Terris-Thule<br></i></p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/unefariusgnome.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nefarius Gnome</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Conjurer</span><br>  Posts: 110<br> <font color=#333333>(10/4/00 5:57:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=33.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: 1 Alternitive</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Until you get to the plains or VP you really shouldn't be spending 8 hours camping a damn spawn. A good number of items can be purchased with plat you know.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->A good number of items can also be purchased on eBay for real money. <br>
